observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Require the Inventory Committee/Property Officer to formulate the plans and strategize on the complete physical count of all its PPE, prepare the RPCPPE and reconcile with the accounting records;

Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the accounting records with the RPCPPE and determine those PPEs to be derecognized; take effect the unrecorded donations; and draw the necessary adjusting entries to reflect in the books the correct balances of the misclassified accounts.

We recommended for the Local Chief Executive to instruct:

The officers and employees concerned for the immediate settlement of their outstanding cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entry of the unrecorded cash advances under Trust Fund; 

The withholding of the salaries of the accountable officers until they make liquidation of their cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the employees concerned and forward the same to COA for the issuance of final demand, and initiate the filing of cases pursuant to Section 128 of PD 1445; and

The Municipal Accountant to stop the grant of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given to the officers and employees is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, and issue a certification that the employee has no outstanding cash advance for every cash advance granted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Treasurer/General Services Officer, and Engineer to comply with the Accounting and Reporting Procedures on Local Road Asset Management System, to perform their mandated duties and responsibilities in the submission of reports and maintenance of records, and to coordinate with each other in order to come up with a reliable balance of the Road Networks account in the financial statements;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting entries to correct the errors in the books of the LGU relative to the computation of depreciation. Likewise, provide necessary disclosures in the notes to financial statements using the prescribed format pertaining to the Road Network account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the GAD Focal Person to:
Coordinate with other offices concerned in spearheading the implementation of GAD related activities;
Submit the documents required under Section 5.2 of the DBM-NEDA-NCRFW Joint Circular No. 2004-1 in support to the Annual GAD Accomplishment Report to facilitate validations of the accomplishments reported to determine compliance on the programs/projects/activities as provided for the General Appropriation Act.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the HRMO to:
Conduct a thorough assessment and evaluation of the existing manpower complement to remove excessive and unnecessary JO workers who are performing redundant functions;
Advise the immediate supervisors to require their job order workers to reflect in the accomplishment report the actual and quantified accomplishments delivered and/or services rendered during the 8-hour work day;
Require the immediate supervisors to make a work schedule acknowledged by the job order personnel concerned and/or enroll the JO workers in the biometric system of the LGU based on the agreed schedule to record their actual attendance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. Municipal Assessor to update the assessment of real properties, prepare the Assessment Roll and submit the report to the Municipal Treasurer on or before the 31st day of December each year;
b. Municipal Treasurer to prepare a Certified List of Taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year.
Update the RPTAR/Index Card to provide information on the unpaid taxes of each taxpayer for the current and previous years;
c. Municipal Accountant to establish/set up RPT and SET Receivables at the beginning of the year based on the RPR/Certified List of Taxpayers with the amount due and collectible, prepared and submitted by the Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended for the Local Chief Executive to instruct:
a. The officers and employees concerned for the immediate settlement of their outstanding cash advances;
b. The Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entry of the unrecorded cash advances under Trust Fund;
c. The withholding of the salaries of the accountable officers until they make liquidation of their cash advances;
d. The Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the employees concerned and forward the same to COA for the issuance of the final demand, and initiate the filing of cases pursuant to Section 128 of PD 1445; and
e. The Municipal Accountant to stop the grant of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given to the officers and employees is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, and issue a certification that the employee has no outstanding cash advance for every cash advance granted.

We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant to prepare:
The JEV to record the valid reconciling items in the books in order to reflect the correct balance of the Cash in Bank account as well as the other pertinent accounts affected;
The BRS for the 3 bank accounts and record the necessary AJEs if any;
The monthly and year-end BRS, and record the necessary adjustments before the FS is finalized.

We recommended that the LCE require:
the Municipal Accountant, Treasurer to strictly comply with the provisions of IPSAS I, Volume I of PPSAS Manual,  Section 20 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs and Sec. 248 of RA 7160. A duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year should be prepared and submitted by the Treasurer to the Municipal Accountant which should serve as the basis for recording the Real Property Tax Receivables/Special Education Tax Receivables at the beginning of the year;
The Municipal Accountant to make adjusting journal entries to take up the unrecorded RPT and SEF Receivables for CY 2019.

We recommended that the LCE require:
The accountable persons concerned to liquidate their outstanding cash advances by issuing Demand Letters;
The Municipal Accountant to delete their names in the payroll until their cash advances are fully settled pursuant to Sec. 3.3.2b of COA Circular No 96-004 and Sec 5.1.3 of COA Circular No 97-002 in case of their failure to comply with the Demand Letters, or else;
The Municipal Accountant to apply proceeds of any claims/amounts due the persons accountable concerned, to their respective cash advances if their net take home pay is insufficient.
The SDO to liquidate all her outstanding cash advances and stop the grant of new cash advance unless she is able to settle all cash advances.

We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Assessor to:
take appropriate steps in order to attain 100% revision of all Tax Declarations of all RPUs in the municipality and submit the updated records to the Provincial Assessor as pre-requisite to the next General Revision and;
coordinate with the Provincial Assessor so that the 4th General Revision of Assessments and Property Classification be made as early as possible.

We recommended that:

a)	The LCE put on hold/stop the release of fund transfers for those recipients who have not implemented the PPAs and submitted liquidation/utilization reports within the prescribed period stated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) and require the concerned Barangay to refund the unimplemented and unutilized fund beyond the timeline;

b)	The Municipal Accountant demand from the recipient Barangay to submit liquidation/utilization reports, review and evaluate the propriety of utilization; and to formulate controls, policies and guidelines in the grant of fund transfers and the timely submission of liquidation/utilization reports; and

We recommended that the Accountant:

a)	Prepare adjusting journal entries to reclassify PPA accounts totaling ₱8,986,420.64 to the appropriate accounts in the financial statements;

b)	Coordinate with the former Accountant and discuss the reconciling item of ₱3,749,633.11 in order to obtain the detailed information for the proper adjustment;   

c)	Prepare adjusting entry to correct the negative balance of (₱1,025,000.00) with a debit of Due to LGUs and credit to Due to NGAs;

d)	Transfer the amount of ₱10,422.84 to the General Fund and record the same as income; and

e)	Verify previous records and coordinate with the DA Regional Office in order to determine the cause of the negative balance of (₱27,992.82) and prepare the necessary adjusting entry.

We recommended that:
The LCE put on hold/stop the release of fund transfers for those recipients who have not implemented the PPAs and submitted liquidation/utilization reports within the prescribed period stated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) and require the concerned Barangay to refund the unimplemented and unutilized fund beyond the timeline;
The Municipal Accountant demand from the recipient Barangay to submit liquidation/utilization reports, review and evaluate the propriety of utilization; and to formulate controls, policies and guidelines in the grant of fund transfers and the timely submission of liquidation/utilization reports; and

We recommended that the Accountant:
Prepare adjusting journal entries to reclassify PPA accounts totaling ₱8,986,420.64 to the appropriate accounts in the financial statements;
Coordinate with the former Accountant and discuss the reconciling item of ₱3,749,633.11 in order to obtain the detailed information for the proper adjustment;
Prepare adjusting entry to correct the negative balance of (₱1,025,000.00) with a debit of Due to LGUs and credit to Due to NGAs;
Transfer the amount of ₱10,422.84 to the General Fund and record the same as income; and
Verify previous records and coordinate with the DA Regional Office in order to determine the cause of the negative balance of (₱27,992.82) and prepare the necessary adjusting entry.

We recommend that:

The LSB  prepare the Annual SEF Budget following the procedure set forth in the Joint Circular and furnish the Local Accountant, Local Treasurer and Local Budget  Officer a  copy of the budget;

The Local Accountant prepare the annual report on SEF Utilization  using the format prescribed in the Joint Circular;

Adhere to the Circular on the allowable expenses chargeable to SEF, and use the appropriate expense account in recording SEF expenses instead of OMOE, and adjustment for the overstatement per Utilization Report with the actual disbursements, if any.
